Let's make a controller named @emph{article}:
@example
art draw controller article show edit
@end example

@emph{show} and @emph{edit} are the name of methods for the controller named @emph{article}.

This will generate both a @strong{controller} and a @strong{view} for @emph{article}:
@example
drawing    controller article
working    Controllers `article.scm'
create     app/controllers/article.scm
working    Views `article'
create     app/views/article/show.html.tpl
create     app/views/article/edit.html.tpl
@end example

These three files are generated:
@example
app/controllers/article.scm
app/views/article/show.html.tpl
app/views/article/edit.html.tpl
@end example

Based on this, the controller @emph{article} will have two methods mapped to the URL rule, @emph{show} and @emph{edit}.
As part of the @emph{view} component. An HTML template is generated for each method. For the @emph{show} method for example, the view file @strong{show.html.tpl} is created.
For the @emph{controller} component, you get a @emph{show} method handler, as:
@example
(article-define show
                (lambda (rc)
                  "<h1>This is article#show</h1><p>Find me in app/views/article/show.html.tpl</p>"
                  ;; TODO: add controller method `show'
                  ;; uncomment this line if you want to render view from template
                  ;; (view-render "show")
                  ))
@end example
Of course, you're free to use or not use these templates. If you want to use the @emph{view template}, just
uncomment the last line @code{(view-render "show")}.

@strong{NOTE:} The views template generated by MVC will defaultly announce FreeJS. The reason was well explained in [BROKEN LINK:  http://www.gnu.org/philosophy/javascript-trap.en.html].
It's optional, you may remove it with your free will, but I put it there in the hope that you can support free software with us.

