@node Init Authentication
@section Init Authentication

GNU Artanis provides flexible mechanism for authentication.

You can use @code{#:auth mode} to define a URL rule handler.
@example
(get "/certain-rule" #:auth mode
     (lambda (rc) ...))
@end example

@strong{mode} can be:
@itemize
@item
SQL as @ref{String Template, , string template}. You can write your own custom SQL string to fetch & check your username and password.
@item
@code{('basic (lambda (rc user passwd) ...))} init Basic Authentication mode. @emph{user} is the username, and @emph{passwd} is the password.
@item
@code{('table table-name username-field passwd-field)} init a common Authentication mode. @strong{The passwd will be encrypted by the default algorithm}.
@item
@code{('table table-name username-field passwd-field crypto-proc)} similar to the above item, but encrypt passwd with crypto-proc.
@item
@code{(table-name crypto-proc)}, so the passwd field will be "passwd" and username will be "username" by default.You can encrypt the passwd with crypto-proc.
@end itemize

Available crypto-proc helper functions listed here:
@example
(string->md5 <string>)
(string->sha-1 <string>)
(string->sha-224 <string>)
(string->sha-256 <string>)
(string->sha-384 <string>)
(string->sha-512 <string>)
@end example

NOTE: Please make sure that the @code{username-field} and @code{passwd-field} must be the same with
the field name specifed in the submit form of you web page code.

For example, if there is a form on you page:
@example
<input type="password" name="passwd">
@end example

Please notice that name of password input was specified to @code{"passwd"}.

Then you should write authentication like this:

@example
(post "/auth" #:auth '(table user "user" "passwd") #:session #t
      (lambda (rc) ...))
@end example

Please notice that the @code{"passwd"} here is the same with what you specified in the form.

@node Basic Authentication
@section Basic Authentication

The HTTP Basic authentication (BA) implementation is the simplest technique for enforcing access control
to web resources, as it doesn't require cookies, session identifiers, or login pages. But rather uses
static, standard HTTP headers, which means that no extra handshakes are necessary for the connection.

The BA mechanism provides no protection for the transmitted credentials. They are merely
encoded with Base64, but not encrypted or hashed in any way. For that reason, Basic Authentication
is typically used over HTTPS.

@emph{@strong{GNU Artanis doesn't support HTTPS at present. There are plans to support it in the future.}}

Let's see a simple example:
@example
(define (my-checker rc user passwd)
  (and (string=? user "jack") (string=? passwd "123")))

(post "/bauth" #:auth `(basic ,checker)
      (lambda (rc)
        (if (:auth rc)
            "auth ok"
            (throw-auth-needed))))
@end example

Another simple way to provide authentication is to compare the passsword stored in a database table:
@example
(post "/bauth" #:auth `(basic Person username passwd)
      (lambda (rc) ... ))
@end example

NOTE: Assuming @strong{username} and @strong{passwd} are columns of the Person table.


You have to define your own checker with the anonymous function @code{(lambda (rc u p) ...)}. #t to show success, and #f to fail.

APIs:

@itemize
@item
@code{(:auth rc)} will check if Basic Authentication succeeded, #f if not.
@item
@code{(throw-auth-needed)} is a useful helper function to ask for auth in client side.
@end itemize

@node Common Authentication
@section Common Authentication

There are multiple authentication methods that can be used by developers. Most of them are sort of tricky hacks. Here are the most common.

The most common, and relatively safe way to authenticate, is to use the POST method, and check the username and passwd from a table in the DB.

There are several ways to provide authentication.

The simplest case is for @ref{String Template}:
@example
#:auth "string-template"
@end example

If you save the account data in a database table, then you can use the table mode:
@example
#:auth `(table ,table-name [,username-field] [,passwd-field] [,salt-field] [,hmac])
@end example

NOTE: The square-braced @strong{[args]} above are optional.

The default values for the optional items are:
@itemize
@item
username-field: username
@item
passwd-field: passwd
@item
salt-field: salt
@end itemize

TODO: remove the brackets for salt-field, as it says below that it's not optional.
And specify whether "optional" means that can be skipped or set to #f to use the default value.

@strong{GNU Artanis requires a salted password, it's not optional.}

So please prepare a field in a table for the salt string. It's your duty to generate a
salt string, please see @ref{Random String Generator}. When authenticating, please specify the
salt field name in the salt-field argument.

For hmac item, please see @ref{HMAC}.

@node Login Authentication
@section Login Authentication

Usually, when doing a login, you will need both @code{#:auth} and @code{#:session} options for a long time session.
The first step is to authenticate, if it's successful, then spawn a new session for this request.

Here is a simple example:

@example
(post "/auth" #:auth '(table user "user" "passwd") #:session #t
      (lambda (rc)
        (cond
         ((:session rc 'check) "auth ok (session)")
         ((:auth rc)
          (:session rc 'spawn)
          "auth ok")
         (else (redirect-to rc "/login?login_failed=true")))))
@end example

@strong{NOTE: The passwd will be encrypted by the default algorithm.}

@node Authenticate checking
@section Authenticate checking

If certain page requires authencation first, then how to check it properly?

In GNU Artanis, the @strong{session-id} is the only token to check if the client has already been authenticated.
By default, the @strong{session-id} is named as @strong{SID} in cookies.
You may use @code{#:with-auth} to do all the works automatically for you.

@example
(get "/dashboard"
  #:with-auth <options>
  (lambda (rc)
    (view-render "dashboard" (the-environment))))
@end example

For example, assuming you have a page @strong{/dashboard} requires login, then you may set @code{#:with-auth} with
certain option. We will explain this option later. Each time user visit @strong{/dashboard} page, GNU Artanis will check if there's
valid @strong{session-id} from client's cookies, if yes, then run the handler to generate the response; if no, then jump to the related
auth failed handler, depends on the option you specified.

Here's available @strong{options}:
@itemize
@item
@code{#t} means the default failure activity: redirect to @strong{/login} page.
@item
URL in string, specify the login page URL. For example, @code{#:with-auth "/admin/login"}.
@item
@code{'status} will return a 401 page with status code 401, which could be checked by cilent.
@item
@strong{Thunk} can be used to generate customized response by users. A thunk is a function without parameter.
For example, @code{#:with-auth (lambda () (scm->json-string '((status . 401) (reason . "No auth"))))}.
This is useful to customize your protocol in JSON for RESTful API.
@end itemize

@strong{NOTE:} Different from other @ref{Shortcuts, , shortcuts}, there's no @code{:with-auth} @strong{apply} for user customized operations
inside the handler. If you use @code{#:with-auth}, then all related works are handled by GNU Artanis.

