@node Introduction 1
@section Introduction

Since version 0.2, GNU Artanis has started to use a strong server core for high concurrency.
Its name is Ragnarok.
In the philosophy of the design of GNU Artanis, everything is meant to be flexible and customizable.
The server core is no exception. In case Ragnarok doesn't suit your needs, you're free to use something else.

Ragnarok doesn't use any popular library for handling events (libev/libuv etc @dots{}).
It's a brand new server core based on epoll and @uref{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delimited_continuation, delimited continuations}.

@node Principles
@section Principles

A basic characteristic of Ragnarok is the use of co-routines. These co-routines are implemented with @uref{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Delimited_continuation, delimited continuations}.
There are no OS/kernel controlled threads, like pthread, for scheduling @emph{request-handlers} in Ragnarok.
All the tasks are scheduled by a userland scheduler. And the task is nothing but just a special continuation.
The key difference between this and a regular @uref{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Call-with-current-continuation#Criticism, full-stack continuation}, is that you can set
limits with precision, instead of having to capture the whole stack.

For researchers, there is a paper published on @uref{http://www.schemeworkshop.org/2016/, ICFP Scheme Workshop 2016 conference} to explain the principle and
the design of GNU Artanis:

@uref{https://github.com/NalaGinrut/artanis/raw/gh-pages/research/scheme16/art2016.pdf, Multi-purpose web framework design based on websockets over HTTP Gateway}.

(to be continued @dots{})

@node Features
@section Features

In Artanis, the request handling can be scheduled even when the socket buffer is full (depends on @code{server.bufsize}).
And let other handlers deal with the requests. Just like the scheduling of an OS, but in userland.

If you have issues with the buffer when scheduling, there's no way to flush before it breaks,
since we can't tell if the scheduling is caused by the buffering or the blocking.

Ragnarok takes advantage of @code{SO_REUSEPORT} introduced in GNU/Linux 3.9 to provide a feature
named @code{server.multi} which can be enabled in the config. This feature allows users to start several
Artanis instances listening to the same port, to take advantage of multi core CPUs, and the Linux Kernel managing the events.

